# Appendix K — SLAT for HTTP and API

Every request and every response can be a SLAT record. Every API
contract can be an assembly of SLAT records. This appendix shows the
pattern.

## Request as SLAT

```motoi-scheme
(http-request
  :method   'post
  :url      \"https://api.example.com/v1/orders\"
  :headers  ((\"content-type\" . \"application/json\")
             (\"authorization\" . \"Bearer ...\"))
  :body     (order :sku \"tulip-brooch\" :qty 1 :price 45.00)
  :ts       #inst \"2026-07-12T14:30:00Z\"
  :timeout  30)
```

Head: `http-request`. Note the body IS a SLAT record — no
serialization ceremony at the outer boundary. When wire time comes,
`slat-write` on the body produces the JSON-ish bytes.

## Response as SLAT

```motoi-scheme
(http-response
  :status   201
  :headers  ((\"content-type\" . \"application/json\"))
  :body     (order-created :id \"ord-42\" :status 'pending)
  :ts       #inst \"2026-07-12T14:30:02Z\"
  :took-ms  1834)
```

Head: `http-response`. Body is again a SLAT record — the parser
turns the JSON-ish response into a real record.

## Endpoint contract as SLAT

```motoi-scheme
(endpoint-contract
  :verb     'post
  :path     \"/v1/orders\"
  :request  (endpoint-contract-record
              :required '(sku qty)
              :optional '(price notes))
  :responses ((201 :body (order-created :required '(id status)))
              (400 :body (error :required '(code message)))
              (401 :body (error :required '(code message))))
  :owner    'marketplace-team)
```

An endpoint contract is a SLAT record. Documentation, mocking,
tests, client SDK generation — all read the same record.

## Wire-time serialization

```motoi-scheme
(define (wire-body body)
  (case (content-type-of body)
    ((json)     (slat->json  body))
    ((form)     (slat->form  body))
    ((protobuf) (slat->pb    body))))
```

She doesn't hardcode wire format — she asks. The record survives
through the wire and back.

## Errors as SLAT

```motoi-scheme
(http-error
  :status  502
  :from    'upstream
  :hint    \"retry with backoff\"
  :ts      #inst \"2026-07-12T14:30:04Z\"
  :run-id  \"cart-run-morning-open\"
  :verb    'schedule-promo)
```

Errors round-trip. Priya reads them; Marcus's Loam projections index
them; Zain's SRE runbooks reference them.

## The API cortex

For every third-party API she uses, her Cortex has a slice.

```motoi-scheme
(cortex-slice
  :region   'etsy-api
  :topic    'listing-post
  :body     (endpoint-contract
              :verb 'post :path \"/v3/application/listings\" ...)
  :sources  '(\"https://developers.etsy.com/documentation/reference/#operation/createListing\")
  :confidence 0.9)
```

She consults the slice before dispatching. If the slice contradicts
her earlier belief, she asks the operator to confirm before running.

